properties.Title: Alberta Emergency Alert - Bridge And Road Closure With Hazardous Materials Release Alert
properties.Summary:
Description: The bridge on Range Road 81, north of Township Road 574 has collapsed, resulting in a hazardous materials release into the Little Paddle River. Range Road 81 is closed from north of Township Road 574 to Township Road 580 until further notice. ### A bridge collapse has occurred and agricultural machinery has entered in the Little Paddle River, leaking fuels into the waterway. County Fire Services is on scene for emergency mitigation and Alberta Environment has been notified for spill clean-up. Heavy equipment has been arranged to remove the machinery. Power may be interrupted to allow for removal of machinery to occur due to power lines in the immediate area. Waters in the Little Paddle River downstream from the bridge are impacted.
Expires: 2020-05-19T13:34:08-06:00

properties.Title: Update To Civil Emergency Alert Issued By Government Of Saskatchewan
properties.Summary:
Description: Update for the Civil Emergency Alert issued by the Government of Saskatchewan. The state of emergency in Saskatchewan remains in effect. UPDATE: Phase 1 of Re-Open Saskatchewan became effective May 4, 2020. All Public Health Orders continue to apply during the implementation of Phase 1 Re-Open Saskatchewan. Continue to monitor and follow all public health orders on the Saskatchewan.ca COVID 19 website. Continue to practice physical distancing. Avoid gatherings with people outside your immediate household. Avoid unnecessary travel. Self-isolate if returning from foreign travel or if experiencing any symptoms. Wash your hands often. Together, we are reducing the risk. We can pull together by staying apart.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potential for heavy downpours and thunderstorms over southern B.C. An unstable atmosphere will lead to widespread showers with the risk of embedded thunderstorms over southern B.C. this afternoon and evening. Total rainfall amounts will be highly variable, ranging from 5 mm to upwards of 30 mm in areas affected by thunderstorms. While pinpointing the exact location and timing of thunderstorms is impossible, the heaviest precipitation is expected east of Okanagan Lake and into the Kootenays tonight. The public and emergency managers should be prepared for sudden and heavy downpours. With snowpacks now primed for melt, the added rainfall could contribute to increased runoff in some areas including the Okanagan and Kootenay-Boundary regions. The River Forecast Centre's flood warnings and advisories can be found at: http://bcrfc.env.gov.bc.ca/warnings/index.htm Showers and a risk of thunderstorms will continue Wednesday, however rainfall totals are expected to be less than tonight. Remember: When thunder roars, go indoors. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2020-05-13T11:43:33-00:00
